	(text "the switch returns to the Due's own ground pin - it is not\na fourth star leg, just the other end of a two-wire harness"
		(exclude_from_sim no)
		(at 208 111 0)
		(effects
			(font
				(size 1.6 1.6)
			)
			(justify left)
		)
		(uuid "5a170004-0000-4000-8000-00000000001f")
	)
	(text_box "REST STATE, POLARITY, AND WHY THE PULL-UP IS ON THE BOARD\n\n  SW1 OPEN     node = 3.3 V                                    logic HIGH\n  SW1 CLOSED   node = 3.3 V x 470 / (4700 + 470) = 0.30 V      logic LOW\n\nagainst the SAM3X's input thresholds at VDDIO = 3.3 V (table 45-2):\n\n  VIH min = 0.7 x VDDIO = 2.31 V    ->  3.3 V clears it by 1.0 V\n  VIL max = 0.3 x VDDIO = 0.99 V    ->  0.30 V clears it by 0.69 V\n\nThe input is therefore never floating, in either switch position, whether or\nnot firmware has configured anything. Active low: a closed switch reads 0.\n\nWHY R3 IS ON THE BOARD AND NOT INSIDE THE CHIP. The SAM3X has a 50-150 kohm\ninternal pull-up on every PIO line, enabled out of reset, and it would do this\njob. It is not the design's pull-up, for two reasons:\n\n*  A rest state that exists only while a particular register holds a particular\n   value is a firmware property. Drawn on the board, it is a property of the\n   hardware, true before the first instruction executes. Same argument as R2 on\n   sheet 3, for the same reason.\n*  100 kohm typical against 100 nF is a 10 ms time constant. The RC below is\n   deliberately twenty times faster than that.\n\nThe internal pull-up is still there and still enabled. 4.7 kohm in parallel with\n100 kohm is 4.5 kohm, which changes nothing that matters."
		(exclude_from_sim no)
		(at 300 40 0)
		(size 274 62.2)
		(margins 1.27 1.27 1.27 1.27)
		(stroke
			(width 0.254)
			(type default)
		)
		(fill
			(type color)
			(color 255 249 214 1)
		)
		(effects
			(font
				(size 1.27 1.27)
			)
			(justify left top)
		)
		(uuid "5a170004-0000-4000-8000-000000000020")
	)
	(text_box "THE DEBOUNCE NETWORK - AND WHAT IT DELIBERATELY DOES NOT DO\n\n  rising edge, switch opens     tau = R3 x C3 = 4.7 kohm x 100 nF = 0.47 ms\n  falling edge, switch closes   tau = (R3 || R4) x C3 = 427 ohm x 100 nF = 43 us\n\nWHAT R4 IS FOR, and it is not the time constant. Without it, C3 discharges\ndirectly through the switch contacts and the peak current is limited only by\ncontact and wire resistance - an amp or more into a few milliohms, on every\nsingle press. That is how a cheap switch welds itself shut. R4 caps it:\n\n  Ipeak = 3.3 V / 470 ohm = 7.0 mA\n\nIt also fixes the closed-state voltage at a defined 0.30 V rather than at\nwhatever the contact resistance happens to be that day.\n\nWHAT THIS NETWORK DOES NOT DO: it does not debounce the switch. Mechanical\ncontacts chatter for 1-10 ms. A 0.47 ms / 43 us pair of time constants filters\nsub-millisecond chatter and guarantees a monotonic edge into the pin, and that\nis exactly what it is sized to do - no more. Making the RC big enough to swallow\n10 ms of bounce on its own would need roughly 100 uF here, and would blur a real\npress into something firmware could no longer time.\n\nThe multi-millisecond settle is firmware's job, and the choice between polling\nwith a settle counter and an edge interrupt plus a timer belongs to the story\nthat writes it. What the hardware guarantees to that firmware is narrow and\nworth stating exactly: the pin sees a clean monotonic transition with no\nsub-microsecond glitches, and it never floats.\n\nThe SAM3X also has a per-pin input glitch filter (PIO_IFER, with a clock divider\nin PIO_SCDR) that firmware may enable on top of this. It is not drawn here\nbecause it is a register, not a wire."
		(exclude_from_sim no)
		(at 300 108.2 0)
		(size 274 73.2)
		(margins 1.27 1.27 1.27 1.27)
		(stroke
			(width 0.254)
			(type default)
		)
		(fill
			(type color)
			(color 255 249 214 1)
		)
		(effects
			(font
				(size 1.27 1.27)
			)
			(justify left top)
		)
		(uuid "5a170004-0000-4000-8000-000000000021")
	)
	(text_box "WHY PD1 / D26 SPECIFICALLY\n\nTable 45-2 specifies an input hysteresis of 150-500 mV on PIO pins \"except PA0,\nPA9, PA26, PA29, PA30, PA31, PB14, PB22, PC[2-9], PC[15-24], PD[10-30], PE[0-4],\nPE15, PE17, PE19, PE21, PE23, PE25, PE29\".\n\nPD1 is not on that list, so it has a Schmitt-trigger input. That matters here and\nessentially nowhere else in this system: this is the one pin fed by a deliberately\nslowed RC edge, and an input without hysteresis crossing its threshold slowly will\nchatter on the noise riding that edge - turning one press into several, which is\nthe precise failure the RC was added to prevent.\n\nPD10 to PD30 are on the exception list. D32 / PD10 is the next convenient pin\nalong this header and it would have been the wrong choice for exactly that reason.\nD28 / PD3, the neighbouring pin on the physical header, is fine.\n\nPD1 is Group 1 in table 45-2 note 2, so its current ceilings are the generous ones.\nIrrelevant for an input drawing microamps - but it means the pin can be repurposed\nlater without going back to the table.\n\nD26 is position 4 on the D22-D53 LHS row (Arduino Due datasheet A000062, section\n6.2.4): the fourth pin in from the end of the header, three past the +5V at\nposition 1. Sheet 3 draws the whole row and carries the warning that goes with it.\n\n+3V3 and the switch's return come from the 24-pin header, positions 4 and 6. That\nis a different header from the one D26 is on, and the two are at opposite ends of\nthe board - check the silkscreen, not the distance."
		(exclude_from_sim no)
		(at 300 187.4 0)
		(size 274 64.4)
		(margins 1.27 1.27 1.27 1.27)
		(stroke
			(width 0.254)
			(type default)
		)
		(fill
			(type color)
			(color 224 240 255 1)
		)
		(effects
			(font
				(size 1.27 1.27)
			)
			(justify left top)
		)
		(uuid "5a170004-0000-4000-8000-000000000022")
	)
	(text_box "IT IS A WALL SWITCH, NOT A BUTTON\n\nSW1 is drawn as an SPST MAINTAINED switch - the kind that stays where you left\nit - because that is what a light switch is. It has no released position to\nreturn to.\n\nThe consequence for firmware: the event is an EDGE, in either direction, and\nboth directions mean the same thing, \"toggle\". There is no press-and-release\npair to match up, and \"up is on\" stops meaning anything the moment something\nelse can also change the light - which is the entire premise of this system.\n\nThat makes SW1 a different input from SW2, the Pi's momentary button on\nsheet 5, even though the two share an identical debounce network. SW2 has a\nrest state it returns to, and only its closing edge is an event.\n\nIf you build this with a momentary push-button in place of SW1 because that is\nwhat is in the drawer, the electrical design is unchanged and the firmware's\nedge handling is not."
		(exclude_from_sim no)
		(at 20 210 0)
